The result of this function represents the course of a DiseaseType if left untreated and to which the person undergoing it has no immunity. The CycLObjectTypeFn function allows us to create new, unquoted collections that allow for CycLExpressions to refer to other instances of CycLExpression. comment: Together with WillardVanOrmanQuine, whose student he was at Harvard, DonaldDavidson is one of the most important figures in 20th-century Anglo-American philosophy. He developed Quine's ideas about meaning and reference in novel and -- by some accounts -- deeper ways, especially in the philosophies of mind, psychology, language and action. Davidson is renowned for a string of stunningly short papers that are now recognized as seminal works in their respective areas: meaning and Tarskian truth theories, events and causation, the logical form of action sentences, radical interpretation, the existence of alternative conceptual schemes. Davidson's interpretation of action sentences as existence claims about event particulars forms the conceptual basis for Cyc's event and actor-slot vocabulary.

A function used for probability statements. (DerivedProbability_RangeFn PROPOSITION), applied to the CycLAssertion PROPOSITION, yields, in the applicable Microtheory, the range of a posteriori probability of the truth of the formula PROPOSITION, given (and depending on) the current state of knowledge of other assertions. This result is a number or range of numbers somewhere within the range 0-1 (either a real number between zero and one, where zero means certainly false and one means certainly true, or an interval between two such numbers). In most microtheories, generally, this refers to the derived range of derived probability that PROPOSITION is true given the probabilities (or probability ranges) of the other CycLAssertions and domainAssumptions of the Microtheory. Contrast this with the predicate form derivedProbability_Range and with the functions DerivedProbabilityFn and PriorProbability_RangeFn. The result of a use of DerivedProbability_RangeFn on a proposition depends at least partially on, and is in some manner derived from or affected by, the probabilities of some or all of the other CycLAssertions in the Microtheory (whether prior, derived or conditional) along with the domainAssumptions. This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.

label: City Section Fn
CitySectionFn
comment: (CitySectionFn ST(1)...ST(N)) denotes the unique urban region (if any) that is completely bounded by parts of each of the streets ST(1) - ST(N). The relative order (but not the absolute position) of the arguments here is important: it should be physically possible to circle completely the bounded area once in a generally clockwise fashion by starting along ST(1) and turning, successively, onto ST(2), ST(3), ..., ST(N), and finally back onto ST(1). In practice, the number of streets N will usually be between 3 and 5 (and the shape of the region returned roughly an N-gon), though N can be as small as 1 if ST(1) is a loop. To have this function return a given street-bounded city section SECTION, one can fill its first argument-place with any of the N streets that borders SECTION, and then continue to fill in the other argument-places according to the order in which one would travel along the other N-1 streets if one were circling SECTION in a generally clockwise fashion (i.e. by making mostly right-hand turns). See also citySectionBoundedBy, CityGridSectionFn and CityBlockFn.

The worm scans computers,                                                                    identifies vulnerable systems, and infects vulnerable systems by installing                                                                itself. The more worms installed, the higher the rate of scanning, which directly decreases the speed of information transfer on the Internet and can cause sporadic but widespread outages among all types of systems.  The purpose of the worm was to infect as many hosts as possible within a limited time span, then use those hosts to stage a denial-of-service attack on http://www.whitehouse.gov. The attack was launched against the IP address of www.whitehouse.gov rather than against the domain name. By moving www.whitehouse.gov to an alternate IP address, the site was kept on-line without difficulty.

This function is used to convert the string representation of an angular distance that determines a longitude value in degree-minute-second format into a proper instance of AngularDistance, using the functions Degree_DMS, Minute_DMS, and Second_DMS. The function makes several assumptions about the format of the input strings:

1. The strings are all of length eight.

2. The first seven characters of the string should all be numerals.

3. The first three characters determine the value for the degree part of the angular distance, which should be between 0 and 180 inclusively.

4. The fourth and fifth characters determine the value for the minute part of the angular distance, and the sixth and seventh characters determine the second part of the angular distance. Both should be nonnegative and strictly less than 60.

5. The eighth character should be either 'E' or 'W'; this character indicates whether the longitude is east or west of the prime meridian; if the character is 'W', then the degree part of the angular distance is translated with a minus sign (-).

Positive examples of valid input strings include '1352106W' and '0042154E'. Negative examples include '1913254E' and '-027932W'. See also the corresponding function EncodeLongitudeToDMSStringFn.

comment: (ContextOfPCWFn WORK) denotes the PropositionalInformationThing associated with WORK. The expression (ContextOfPCWFn WORK) serves the same role as expressions that denote the PIT of a particular physical instance of WORK (such as (PITOfIBTFn COPY67OFWORK)), except that (ContextOfPCWFn WORK) denotes the PIT of the abstract object WORK, which a copy of WORK instantiates. For example if we think of (ContextOfPCWFn WORK) as the entirety of the content of WORK, (ContextOfPCWFn MobyDickNovel) denotes the entirety of the content of MobyDick, whereas (PITOfIBTFn Copy787OfMobyDick) denotes the entirety of the content of Copy787OfMobyDick. Note that we assert as a default rule that whatever is true in the PIT of a PropositionalConceptualWork is true in the PIT an instantiation of that work, but not the converse. (A copy of Moby Dick may contain an introductory critical essay, or publication information -- information not contained in MobyDickNovel. Thus the PIT of a copy of MobyDick may be such that more things are true in it than are true in the PIT of MobyDickNovel). This rule is made default to account for the fact that a copy of a book remains a copy of Moby Dick even after damage which results in a small loss of the information that it contains.

An unreifiable, binary TermMacroFunction that takes two quoted instances of CycLPropositionalSentence and returns a Real0_1. Intuitively, (ConditionalProbabilityFn HYPOTHESIS EVIDENCE) denotes the probability (in the current context) that HYPOTHESIS holds, given only the information that EVIDENCE holds. Formally, it is shorthand for: 
(QuotientFn
  (ProbabilityFn
    (and HYPOTHESIS EVIDENCE))
  (ProbabilityFn EVIDENCE)).
Note that this is undefined when (ProbabilityFn EVIDENCE) = 0.

Consider, e.g., the following CycLNonAtomicTerm: 

(ConditionalProbabilityFn
  (fanOf GeorgeWBush WillieNelson)
  (originallyFromRegion GeorgeWBush Texas_State)).
Intuitively, this denotes the probability that Bush is a Willie Nelson fan, given only the information that he (Bush) is originally from Texas. Formally, it is shorthand for: 
(QuotientFn
  (ProbabilityFn
    (and
      (fanOf GeorgeWBush WillieNelson)
      (originallyFromRegion GeorgeWBush Texas_State)))
  (ProbabilityFn
    (originallyFromRegion GeorgeWBush Texas_State))).
See also this function's corresponding predicate, conditionalProbability.
label: Conditional Probability Fn
ConditionalProbabilityFn

comment: A function used for probability statements. (ConditionalProbabilitySetFn PROPOSITION SETOFPROPOSITIONS) applied to an CycLAssertion and a set of CycLAssertions, results in the probability of PROPOSITION being true given that all the propositions in SETOFPROPOSITIONS are known to be true, in the applicable Microtheory. It yields a real number between zero and one, where zero means certainly false and one means certainly true. In most microtheories, generally, this ConditionalProbabilitySetFn refers to the conditional probability that PROPOSITION is true given only that the propositions that are elements of SETOFPROPOSITIONS, and the domainAssumptions accessible in the applicable Microtheory, are true, without regard to any further evidence or the truth of any other assertions. See also ConditionalProbabilityFn, PriorProbabilityFn, DerivedProbabilityFn, conditionallyIndependent, and the predicate version of this function: conditionalProbabilitySet. This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.

(CollectionDifferenceFn INCLUDECOL EXCLUDECOL) is the collection DIFFCOL such that a given THING is an instance of DIFFCOL if and only if THING is an instance of INCLUDECOL but not an instance of EXCLUDECOL.

For example, (CollectionDifferenceFn MailOrderCompany Pharmacy) is the collection of mail order companies that are not pharmacies.

Note that if (disjointWith INCLUDECOL EXCLUDECOL) holds, then DIFFCOL is just INCLUDECOL itself. If (genls INCLUDECOL EXCLUDECOL) holds, then DIFFCOL is empty (i.e. (extent DIFFCOL TheEmptySet) holds).

comment: A PredicateDenotingFunction used to convert "de dicto" cognitive attitude predicates (see PropositionalAttitudeSlot) into their "de re" counterparts (see DeReAttitudePredicate). (DeReVersionFn PROP-ATT-SLOT) is the cognitive attitude predicate DE-RE-PRED that is the ternary "de re version" of the binary PROP-ATT-SLOT. The extensions (see relationExtension) of PROP-ATT-SLOT and DE-RE-PRED are correlated roughly as follows. (i) If (PROP-ATT-SLOT AGENT SENT) holds, and the Nth-place term within SENT denotes something, then (DE-RE-PRED AGENT SENT N) holds. (ii) If (DE-RE-PRED AGENT SENT N) holds, then there must be some term NEWTERM that is codenoting (and possibly identical) with the Nth-place term OLDTERM within SENT such that (PROP-ATT-SLOT AGENT SENT-PRIME) holds, where SENT-PRIME is the result of replacing OLDTERM with NEWTERM in the Nth-place of SENT. For example, (DeReVersionFn beliefs) is believesOfArg. An agent's having a de dicto belief with respect to a given sentence entails her having analogous de re beliefs regarding each thing denoted by some constituent of that sentence; and an agent's having a de re belief regarding a given thing entails her having some analogous de dicto belief with respect to a sentence having an immediate constituent that denotes that thing.

A unary GenlsPreservingFunction (q.v.) that takes a given type of tangible object to the collection of all objects that are shaped like objects of that type. More precisely, (CommonShapeFn OBJTYPE) is the (most inclusive) specialization of ShapedObject all of whose instances have the same (most specific) shape shared by all non-pathological instances of OBJTYPE.

For example, (CommonShapeFn DomesticCat) is the collection of all cat-shaped objects, which includes not just cats themselves, but also cat-shaped toys, cookie-cutters, cushions, space-regions, etc.

The fact that this function returns the most inclusive collection of OBJTYPE-shaped things ensures that (CommonShapeFn DomesticCat) includes all (not just some) cat-shaped objects. The fact that the function returns the collection all of whose instances have the most specific shape common to (non-pathological) OBJTYPEs ensures that (CommonShapeFn DomesticCat) does not include, say, all animal-shaped objects.

A binary MathematicalFunctionOnScalars and an extension of the arithmetic subtraction operation to ScalarIntervals (q.v.) generally. When applied to two arithmetically-comparable scalars, MINUEND and SUBTRAHEND, DifferenceFn yields the scalar that is the result of subtracting SUBTRAHEND from MINUEND. For example, (DifferenceFn 88 11) is 77 and (DifferenceFn (Kilogram 4.2) (Kilogram 3)) is (Kilogram 1.2).

Note that when MINUEND and SUBTRAHEND are not arithmetically-comparable, (DifferenceFn MINUEND SUBTRAHEND) is undefined. For example, (DifferenceFn (MinutesDuration 1) (Meter 3)) is undefined, since (MinutesDuration 1) is a Time_Quantity and (Meter 3) is a Distance, and time-quantities are not comparable with distances.

For addition, see PlusFn.

This function is used to convert the string representation of an angular distance that determines a latitude value in degree-minute-second format into a proper instance of AngularDistance, using the functions Degree_DMS, Minute_DMS, and Second_DMS. The function makes several assumptions about the format of the input strings:

1. The strings are all of length seven.

2. The first six characters of the string should all be numerals.

3. The first two characters determine the value for the degree part of the angular distance, which should be between 0 and 90 inclusively.

4. The third and fourth characters determine the value for the minute part of the angular distance, and the fifth and sixth characters determine the second part of the angular distance. Both should be nonnegative and strictly less than 60.

5. The seventh character should be either 'N' or 'S'; this character indicates whether the latitude is above or below the equator; if the character is 'S', then the degree part of the angular distance is translated with a minus sign (-).

Positive examples of valid input strings include '352106N' and '042154S'. Negative examples include '913254N' and '-27932S'.
label: Decode String To DMS Latitude Fn
DecodeStringToDMSLatitudeFn

label: Cyc's knowledge about computer vulnerability

comment: ComputerVulnerabilityMt is the most general microtheory encompassing knowledge about the electronic vulnerabilities computers have as attributes. The microtheory contains two broad areas of knowledge: (1) Definitions for the upper level -- i.e. non-leaf -- nodes in the computer vulnerability hierarchy, (2) definitions of the upper level -- i.e. non-leaf -- nodes in the software fault hierarchy, and (3) definitional knowledge for predicates that utilize this vocabulary to represent vulnerability and fault knowledge. Two classes of knowledge are explicitly excluded from this microtheory and should be placed in a more specific microtheory (or microtheories): instance level, or leaf-node vulnerability and fault attributes, and knowledge about the faults in specific computer programs.

comment: A function used for probability statements. (DerivedProbabilityFn PROPOSITION), applied to the CycLAssertion PROPOSITION, yields, in the applicable Microtheory, the a posteriori probability of the truth of the formula PROPOSITION, given (and depending on) the current state of knowledge of other assertions. The result is a real number between zero and one, where zero means certainly false and one means certainly true. In most microtheories, generally, this refers to the derived probability that PROPOSITION is true given the probabilities or truth values of the other CycLAssertions and domainAssumptions of the Microtheory. Contrast this with the predicate form derivedProbability and with the functions PriorProbabilityFn and DerivedProbability_RangeFn. The result of DerivedProbabilityFn depends at least partially on, and is in some manner derived from or affected by, the probabilities of some or all of the other CycLAssertions in the Microtheory (whether prior, derived or conditional) along with the domainAssumptions. See also conditionalProbability. This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.

label: CVS
ConcurrentVersionsSystem-TheProgram
comment: ConcurrentVersionsSystem_TheProgram ("CVS") is a version control system. It is useful for recording the history of source files. CVS stores all versions of a file in a single file in a clever way that only stores the differences between versions. CVS also helps you if you are part of a group of people working on the same project. It is all too easy to overwrite each others' changes unless you are extremely careful. Some editors, like GnuEmacs, try to make sure that the same file is never modified by two people at the same time. Unfortunately, if someone is using another editor, that safeguard will not work. CVS solves this problem by insulating the different developers from each other. Every developer works in his own directory, and CVS merges the work when each developer is done.

label: Droggn

comment: This card game is a version of Tarot_CardGame which developed in Austria. There is a tradition among some of the players that this game was introduced from France or the French part of Switzerland. Some of them called it Franzosisches Tarock, to distinguish it from the Tarock games with 54 cards played in other parts of Austria (Konigrufen_CardGame). Its introduction was said to be associated with Andreas Hofer, the Tyrolean hero who stood against Napoleon. Others, however, contend that it was imported from northern Italy by Italian door-to-door salesmen ('kraxn-drogar') who used to sell their goods in the Tyrol. In recent times it seems to be played only in the Stubai valley, south west of Innsbruck.

label: the convex hull of ______
ConvexHullFn
comment:
A unary function that takes a given two- or three-dimensional spatial thing to its intangible "convex hull". Let HULL = (ConvexHullFn OBJECT). If OBJECT is a TwoDimensionalThing, then HULL is the entire one-dimensional boundary (see ClosedLinearObject) of the minimal convex 2-D space region that spatiallySubsumes OBJECT (see #$ConvexSpaceRegion and Surface). If OBJECT is a ThreeDimensionalThing, then HULL is the entire closed two-dimensional surface (see ClosedSurfaceRegion) of the minimal convex 3-D space region that subsumes OBJECT.

Note that the dimensionality of HULL is always one less than that of OBJECT. Also note that, while OBJECT might or might not be a SpatiallyContinuousThing, HULL is spatially-continuous in either case.

See also the corresponding predicate convexHullOf. To represent the whole convex space region bounded by a given object's convex hull, use MinimalSubsumingConvexSpaceRegionFn.

An instance of CollectionDenotingFunction useful for indicating when the collection that stands in arg2 of some instance of BinaryPredicate changes for some thing. (CollectionValueChangingFn BIN_PRED THING COLL-VAL1 COLL-VAL2) denotes the collection of events in which the value for the instance of #$BinaryAttributePredicate ATT_PRED for THING changes from COLL-VAL1 to COLL-VAL2. For instance, (CollectionValueChangingFn educationLevel Bob FirstGradeLevel SecondGradeLevel) denotes the collection of events in which Bob goes from having a first grade education level to the second grade education level. This function is a collection form of SlotValueChangingFn, after which it is patterned.

A binary SubcollectionDenotingFunction that takes a Collection and a Set_Mathematical to the largest subcollection of the former that is a subsetOf the latter. (CollectionSubsetFn COL SET) is, by definition, the collection of all and only those instances of COL that are also elements of SET.

For example, 

(CollectionSubsetFn
  TemporalThing
  (TheSetOf ?X (isa ?X TemporallyContinuousThing)))

is the collection of all and only temporal things that are temporally-continuous.

See also the corresponding predicate subcollectionOfAndSubsetOf.
